english:
  title: Preface to the Anthology of Selected Refinements
  author: Lee Sek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    To organize writings by era follows the method of Confucius. Thus the ancient records were named the Documents of Yu, Xia, Shang, and Zhou. Similarly, to organize poetry by form also follows Confucius's method. Thus the poems of the feudal states were called the "Airs," while the poems of the Son of Heaven were called the "Greater Odes" and "Eulogies." Confucius inherited the way of Yao and Shun, and took as his model the achievements of Kings Wen and Wu. He refined the Poetry and Documents, established the rites and music, brought forth governance, and rectified human nature and feelings—unifying customs and laying the eternal foundation for universal peace. As it is said, "Since humanity began, none has surpassed the Master." Can we doubt this truth?

    Yet amid the devastation of Qin, barely did the texts survive from the walls of Confucius's sanctuary. The way of Poetry and Documents vanished into confusion until the Tang dynasty, when Han Yu alone understood the importance of honoring Confucius, and letters were thereby transformed. Yet his single essay "On Original Nature" suffices to reveal both his gains and shortcomings. In the Song dynasty, those who revered Han Yu and studied ancient prose were but a few—Ouyang Xiu and others. Yet in clarifying the learning of Confucius and Mencius, rejecting the teachings of Laozi and the Buddha, and illuminating ten thousand generations, this was the achievement of Zhou and Cheng alone. When the Song dynasty fell, their teachings flowed northward. Master Xu of Lu'ai employed this learning to serve the Yuan emperor Kublai Khan, and the governance of the Zhongtong and至元 eras all emerged from this. Alas, how glorious!

    My friend Jin Gyeong-suk sighed and lamented: "Wenzhongzi extended the Classics and presumed to comment upon the Analects—an overreach, though scholars have forgiven it. Thus I, without weighing my shallowness, have compiled what I have heard of old and brought it to the present day. Collecting the poems and prose of various authors concerning civilization, human nature, and feeling into several volumes..." An official then came and said: "Jin Gyeong-suk has not been able to realize his aspirations in this world, and now age has overtaken him. Even I grieve for this. Fortunately he has gathered the classics into a single record, which the Master has named the Six Wings of the Zhou Rites. He has also compiled an anthology of ancient and modern poetry and prose, which the Master has named the Anthology of Selected Refinements. The 'Selected' takes from the Anthology of Literature by the Prince of Zhao Ming; 'Refinements' takes from the Tang Literary Essences by Yao Xuan. The meaning is to extract what is finest. When one selects, one refines; when one refines, one selects. Thus we praise the author's work and inspire the student. Please, Master, grant us a preface to crown these pages."

    I could not demur, so I have written this preface myself: When I was young, I traveled through the Central Plain and heard the scholars say that prose follows the Han model and poetry follows the Tang model—though I did not understand why. Upon entering the Forest of Brushes at court, the realm descended into chaos, my mother grew old, and I resigned my post to return home. Mistakenly favored by Lord Gongmin, I have served in office, striving merely to avoid error, unable to devote myself fully to learning. The little knowledge I gained has nearly all faded away. Now seeing how Gyeong-suk has built something so noble, how can my brow not glisten with sweat?

    Yet I know that if this collection endures, my preface endures with it. If my preface endures, my name endures. Why should I refuse? In future days, should someone compile a book on Chinese letters following the model of Confucius's selections—the Oath of Lu, the Eulogies of Lu and Shang—and place even one or two pieces at the end of these pages, what great fortune that would be! Why should I refuse?
  footnotes:
    - The 'Oath of Lu' (魯誓) and the 'Eulogies' refer to Confucian canonical texts that served as models for literary selection and preservation.
    - Yi Saek references his time as a Hanlin academician (翰林官) during the turbulent transition from Goryeo to Joseon, a period when he struggled to balance official duty with scholarly pursuits.
    - The allusion to 'forehead glistening with sweat' (泚顙) is an expression of deep admiration and emotion.
    - The work reflects the Neo-Confucian emphasis on proper literary transmission and the preservation of cultural orthodoxy during the unstable late Goryeo period.
